Issues.Body:
When changing DepdendencyProperties there is an equalitycheck to prevent unecessary events when the value is actually the same.

However, this is based on the Type of the DependencyProperty and uses `Object.Equals` for string and valuetypes and `Object.ReferenceEquals` for eveything else.
So if the DependencyProperty is of Type Object, it will allways use `Object.ReferenceEquals.`

See here
https://referencesource.microsoft.com/#WindowsBase/Base/System/Windows/DependencyObject.cs,3453

```
/// <summary>
///     Helper method to compare two DP values
/// </summary>
private bool Equals(DependencyProperty dp, object value1, object value2)
{
    if (dp.IsValueType || dp.IsStringType)
    {
        // Use Object.Equals for Strings and ValueTypes
        return Object.Equals(value1, value2);
    }
    else
    {
        // Use Object.ReferenceEquals for all other ReferenceTypes
        return Object.ReferenceEquals(value1, value2);
    }
}
```

The problem is, that valuetypes get boxed and hence will allways fail the ReferenceEquality check.

So my proposal is to change that if to something like this:


```
/// <summary>
///     Helper method to compare two DP values
/// </summary>
private bool Equals(DependencyProperty dp, object value1, object value2)
{
    if (dp.IsValueType || dp.IsStringType)
    {
        // Use Object.Equals for Strings and ValueTypes
        return Object.Equals(value1, value2);
    }
    else
    {
        // For ObjectTypes check if both values are the same value or string type
        // and if so, use Object.Equals aswell since ReferenceEquals will allways fail due to boxing.
        if(dp.IsObjectType)
        {
            Type t = value1?.GetType();
             
             // If values have different types, they cant be equal.
             if(t != value2?.GetType())
                return false;
            
            // They can both be null
            if(t == null) 
                return true;

            if(t.IsValueType || t == typeof(string))
                 return Object.Equals(value1, value2);
        }

        // Use Object.ReferenceEquals for all other ReferenceTypes
        return Object.ReferenceEquals(value1, value2);
    }
}

```
That code probably isnt the most efficient way of doing this, but you get the idea.

While this adds more complexity to the EqualityCheck it will reduce the ammount of events that will result from those "false positives". 


